"work": "Them There Eyes", "composer": "Maceo Pinkard", "performers": [{"id": "15314", "name": "Bobby Tucker", "qid": "Q888698", "roles": ["piano"]}, {"id": "53224", "name": "Remo Palmier", "qid": "Q2143069", "roles": ["guitar"]}, {"id": "56192", "name": "Billie Holiday", "qid": "Q104358", "roles": ["vocalist"]}, {"id": "62623", "name": "Denzil Best", "qid": "Q488329", "roles": ["drums"]}, {"id": "62624", "name": "John Levy", "qid": "Q1374878", "roles": ["double_bass"]}]}, {"label": "God Bless the Child", "work": "God Bless the Child", "composer": "Billie Holiday", "performers": [{"id": "15314", "name": "Bobby Tucker", "qid": "Q888698", "roles": ["piano"]}, {"id": "53224", "name": "Remo Palmier", "qid": "Q2143069", "roles": ["guitar"]}, {"id": "56192", "name": "Billie Holiday", "qid": "Q104358", "roles": ["vocalist"]}, {"id": "62623", "name": "Denzil Best", "qid": "Q488329", "roles": ["drums"]}, {"id": "62624", "name": "John Levy", "qid": "Q1374878", "roles": ["double_bass"]}]}, {"label": "You Better Go Now", "work": "You Better Go Now", "composer": "Irvin Graham", "performers": [{"id": "15314", "name": "Bobby Tucker", "qid": "Q888698", "roles": ["piano"]}, {"id": "53224", "name": "Remo Palmier", "qid": "Q2143069", "roles": ["guitar"]}, {"id": "56192", "name": "Billie Holiday", "qid": "Q104358", "roles": ["vocalist"]}, {"id": "62623", "name": "Denzil Best", "qid": "Q488329", "roles": ["drums"]}, {"id": "62624", "name": "John Levy", "qid": "Q1374878", "roles": ["double_bass"]}]}, {"label": "No More", "work": "No More", "composer": "Salvadore Camarata", "performers": [{"id": "15314", "name": "Bobby Tucker", "qid": "Q888698", "roles": ["piano"]}, {"id": "53224", "name": "Remo Palmier", "qid": "Q2143069", "roles": ["guitar"]}, {"id": "56192", "name": "Billie Holiday", "qid": "Q104358", "roles": ["vocalist"]}, {"id": "62623", "name": "Denzil Best", "qid": "Q488329", "roles": ["drums"]}, {"id": "62624", "name": "John Levy", "qid": "Q1374878", "roles": ["double_bass"]}]}, {"label": "Easy Living", "work": "Easy Living", "composer": "Ralph Rainger", "performers": [{"id": "15314", "name": "Bobby Tucker", "qid": "Q888698", "roles": ["piano"]}, {"id": "53224", "name": "Remo Palmier", "qid": "Q2143069", "roles": ["guitar"]}, {"id": "56192", "name": "Billie Holiday", "qid": "Q104358", "roles": ["vocalist"]}, {"id": "62623", "name": "Denzil Best", "qid": "Q488329", "roles": ["drums"]}, {"id": "62624", "name": "John Levy", "qid": "Q1374878", "roles": ["double_bass"]}]}], "quotes": [{"speaker": "John Levy", "qid": "Q1374878", "text": "we got a job to go to 52nd Street and open in the Onyx Club. And in those days they gave you a long term deal, so the deal was for six months. And Jimmy Jones, I’m sort of ahead of myself, because actually Jimmy Jones joined the group — Raymond Walters was the first pianist with us, and he worked with us maybe in Chicago for maybe about two or three months. And then Jimmy Jones and I had been friends, I knew him as a player and I recommended that he come on with us. And that’s how the real Stuff Smith Trio got together. And then we came to New York and opened in the Onyx Club in August of 1944. And then I met Joe Glaser for the first time — this agent and everything. And as I said I developed an excellent relationship with him, and learned a lot about the inside of the business and how it all worked, which helped me later on when I finally went into that end of the business. We worked there at the Onyx Club — I guess we stayed there about a year. And I think I left, I was the first one to leave the trio. I went with Don Byas for a while, and then did a lot of recordings with Ink Spots and you name it, different jazz groups, and then Errol Garner. I made a series of records with Errol, just four sides actually, for Savoy Records with Errol Garner. And from that, one thing to the other until we get to 1948. In 1948 I got a call from Bobby Tucker to join him to work with Billie Holiday. And Billie Holiday had been in Lexington, Kentucky for a rehab for the dope. And she was coming out, and she was going to do a Carnegie Hall concert. And this was 1948. So we got together, and Denzel Best was the drummer. And we rehearsed out in New Jersey at Bobby Tucker’s house, where Billie Holiday was staying. And rehearsed for that. And I can’t remember the exact date in 1948 that we played Carnegie Hall, but we played it. It was my first time in Carnegie Hall. It was the first time that Carnegie Hall had ever had just a trio playing on stage, you know, so I mean the union made a ruling for the future that you’d have to have a minimum number of twelve musicians to play Carnegie Hall.", "caption": "John Levy recalls Billie Holiday's 1948 Carnegie Hall debut", "conf": "high", "first_person": null, "doc_title": "John Levy interviewed by Monk Rowe, Majesty of the Seas, May 31, 1995", "collection": "hamilton", "url": "https://litsdigital.hamilton.edu/collections/object/john-levy-interviewed-monk-rowe-majesty-seas-may-31-1995"}, {"speaker": "John Levy", "qid": "Q1374878", "text": "My name is John Mitchell. I’m a staff writer for the Los Angeles Times. Today is December 10th, 2006. We’re in the home of John Levy and his wife Devra Hall at 1827 Coolidge Avenue, Altadena, California. We’re here as part of the Smithsonian’s Jazz Oral History Project to record John Levy’s story. A former bass player, John has been managing the careers of music artists since 1951. In his musical prime he played the bass when jazz was at its heyday on New York’s 52nd Street. Duke Ellington wanted him in his orchestra. Billie Holiday hired him for her comeback concert at Carnegie Hall in 1948. Then John put away his upright to sit behind a desk and manage the careers of artists. He had a rich stable of clients: George Shearing, Dakota Staton, Betty Carter, Lou Donaldson, Herbie Mann, Les McCann, Ernie Andrews, Randy Crawford, Brook Benton, Ahmad Jamal, Freddie Hubbard, Cannonball Adderley, Wes Montgomery, Joe Williams, Shirley Horn, Ramsey Lewis, Roberta Flack, Donny Hathaway, Eddie Harris, Johnny Hartman, Stanley Turrentine, Diane Reeves, Sarah Vaughan, Nancy Wilson, and the list goes on. So much history. So many lives touched. We want to start at the beginning. So John, why don’t you start by giving us your full name and spelling it for us.", "caption": "Billie Holiday's 1948 comeback concert at Carnegie Hall", "conf": "high", "first_person": false, "doc_title": "John Levy — Smithsonian Jazz Oral History", "collection": "si", "url": "https://amhistory.si.edu/jazz/Levy-John/Levy_John_Transcript.pdf"}], "featured_people": [{"qid": "Q104358", "id": "56192", "name": "Billie Holiday"}, {"qid": "Q888698", "id": "15314", "name": "Bobby Tucker"}, {"qid": "Q488329", "id": "62623", "name": "Denzil Best"}, {"qid": "Q5496153", "id": "6361", "name": "Fred Robbins"}, {"qid": "Q1374878", "id": "62624", "name": "John Levy"}, {"qid": "Q2143069", "id": "53224", "name": "Remo Palmier"}]}